IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, originally had the complex name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM took over until 1924 – originally it was a brand used for subsidiaries in Canada and South America.
The foundation for later IBM gave the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the eighties of the nineteenth century.
They owned technologies such as famous "pipe machines," i.e. hours recording employees' arrival and departure.
The architect of the new company was the businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who was also chairman of the company’s supervisory board until 1930.
Flint hired the head of the competitive company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him manage the company.
The leader then concealed the founder of IBM – on Watson’s ideas is built the unbeatable corporate culture and identity.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of machinery for business - from meat and cheese cutting machines to cash.
During the first four years of Watson’s headquarters, the turnover has doubled to nine million dollars and the company has started its extensive expansion to all continents.
Watson was so unnecessary to the company that after almost forty years in the chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
