How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time sold in the vast majority only trips to the countries of the socialist block, since travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists then traveled for a holiday to the sea to the NDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on Crimea near the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime approached the West and the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of socialism was that the citizens of the socialist block (i.e. the Czechoslovak) were not allowed to travel individually freely even within the socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a call letter from this country, otherwise the individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to stand the front overnight with a sleeper or have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
However, it was not won either.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was the condition for travel to the West, was not given to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for the journey to the West.
The most frequently, however, the Czechs spent their holidays in the country, which resulted in a large number of chats and chalets that the Czechs purchased and this habit survives to the present day.
The travel of the Czechs has experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 holiday in the NDR or Bulgaria was our maximum, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
The enormous paradox that we don’t realize today is that it was not possible to travel freely to the most popular Croatia for us until 1989, since it was part of the Yugoslavia at the time.
At the end of the 1990s, the visa obligation to neighboring Western European countries was abolished, which initiated a huge wave of short-term visits primarily to Austrian Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovak people could not take a long trip to the West, everyone wanted to see at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, the Czechs' trips slept in parks in tents, as our earnings at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a pension.
A typical feature of traveling the Czechs was at this time driving their own food, conserve, salads, etc., to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely exchanged Czech crown, thus our tourists could finally after many decades freely buy the Western currency.
However, our living standards and the average wages have increased, resulting around 1997 in another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have started regularly preparing charter airlines since 1997, making air travel unbelievably slower due to the possibility of contracting quantitative discounts compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had already a visa-free contact to almost all the developed countries of the world, except the United States, which continued to make our travel easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution travel occurred in the year 2000, when the first direct charter flight to the exotic was made from the Czech Republic due to a large demand, it was to Thailand.
From this year so every year they fly with Czech tourists direct charters to warm distant countries, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic already to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visiting around 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolution development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. canceled the visa for Czech tourists and thus our country was definitely ranked among the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50,3%) and for the first time in history spent for one foreign holiday including costs at the place of residence more than 15 thousand CZK per person.
