Walls Have Eyes: How Scientists Explore You on Facebook
Before Anders Behring Breivik became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, he was just another young man who presented his anti-immigration opinions on the internet.
On Monday, Braivik, who admitted to the July murder, after which 77 people were killed in Norway, took part in his first public trial.
Although Breivik could act alone, he was definitely not lonely in the cyber space: during the preparation of the attack he spent a lot of time on the computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting right-wing groups on social networks.
After the tragedy of this summer, scientists want to learn more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just go out on Facebook.
“We realized that getting them isn’t really so difficult at all,” says Jamie Bartlett, the chief author of a recent British research team’s report on European digital populism.
The stock of personal information on Facebook is so comprehensive, says Bartlett, that it was enough for scientists to simply take advantage of advertising on the site and thus with absolute accuracy determine the demographic group they are looking for – something that marketing professionals have done for years.
Bartlett's team across Europe found half a million fans of right-wing groups, focusing attention on them and sending them ads. However, instead of calling them to a newly created group or offering some dietary products through them, they invited them to fill out a questionnaire with questions about their level of education, their relationship with violence and optimism with regard to their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans from 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without having to leave the office at all.
"This is a completely new way of conducting research," Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are all the young men who are suppressed by the growing rate of immigration.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism even with off-line activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind the computer screen."
The work of the DEMOS team is just one of the examples of how Facebook becomes a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists and political researchers use this site to study everything, from health problems to social trends hiding with state updates, wall posts and the "Like" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. Each of them daily will provide an average of three different data, making this social network literally a "information supernova", which stands behind the development of many new research. The number of academic works, in whose name the word Facebook appears, increased compared to the state five years ago to almost 800%.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook lies in giving them the opportunity to study people without having to bother them somewhere on the street.
"In the past it was true that when you wanted to do a survey among people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
“You should get into a party where you would never be left,” says Bartlett.
“This is all Facebook breaks down – you just go directly to them.”
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify a social-health problem and avoid them.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moren from the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that university students who broke their drunk outcomes on Facebook were much more threatened by the problem of alcoholism than students who silent about this topic.
Moren suggests that fellow students of the site monitor and come with an offer of help to a student who publishes too many drunk status.
“The problem cannot be solved unless you can diagnose it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Moreno and director of the Center for Children’s Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle.
“We found a way to identify threatened children that we would otherwise have no chance to discover.”
Facebook is constantly investigating the data of its users.
The information team of the site has drawn up statistics regarding the context of relations status and Valentine's Day, the 2010 election participation and the coefficient of people's satisfaction (mainly using the information to which they had access - internet freedom defenders have long claimed that the site should make its information treasure available to research and others).
But Facebook users know that the page follows them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of kilometers away, they need the page to provide their personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don’t even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules regarding how to collect data off-line. however, online data is accessible to everyone.
