Climate disadvantage breaks the economy
During the first year of the government of Maria Lopez Valdeza, unemployment and unreliability increased in Sinaloa, foreign investments decreased and with them the economy increased.
The 2011 year will be recorded in the economic history of Sinaloa. This is the first year of the government of Maria Lopez Valdeza, which itself calls the government of change. This government has brought great expectations in terms of economic progress, however, due to the unfavourable climate conditions at the beginning of the year, no growth has been and even the main indicators of economic development have decreased.
Low February temperatures caused millions of losses in agriculture, limited the possibilities of growth of the state economy, are aware of a 3.6% decrease in economic activity in the first half of this year.
According to the report on the damages caused by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, damages were recorded on 582,835 hectares of cultivated soil, of which 78,03% were completely destroyed and on the remaining 21,07% partial damages were detected.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a constant increase in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state recorded an increase in the first three quarters. From January to March, 55 053 inhabitants of the state of Sinaloa were unemployed, representing the unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate increased to 5.28% and between July and August, the average unemployment rate continued to rise and reached the value of 6.19%, which represents approximately 74,000 unemployed.
Less liquidity
According to Gerard Lopez Cervantes, Director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on the steps that have been taken at the level of public policy.
“We are witnessing an increasing unemployment that is linked to various factors. These include, among other things, the loss of liquidity in the market due to resource restrictions as a result of a legislation approved by Congress in connection with the fight against money laundering. For people who illegally possess dollars, it is not easy to earn them, invest them or use them for something,” he emphasized.
Stop the migration
López Cervantes said that a demographic factor is also involved in the growth of unemployment.
“The number of people who leave for work abroad, to the United States, has decreased, on the one hand due to the reasons of difficult entry and then also because even if these people get outside the border, it’s hard for them to get a job.
Unreliability
According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the employed population in the state works without giving benefits to the social security administration.
Unemployment and unreliability are added to other characteristics of the labour market, such as low wages. In this administrative territory, the lowest wages from all over the country, according to the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Planning registers.
The average monthly income of workers in the state of Sinaloa was 5 352 pesets by September, deep below the national average, which moves to the amount of 7 375 pesets.
Reduction of Foreign Direct Investments
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, the most significant decline in foreign direct investments in the last 10 years was also recorded in 2011. According to the Ministry of Finance, in the period from January to June, foreign direct investments reached 630 697 dollars, which represents a decline of 87.74% compared to the amount of 5 143 312 dollars in the same period in the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the state government reports investments of 17 280 million pesets per year.
Debt
In connection with the scenario of economic decline the government of this state requested in July the State Congress to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos. This would be intended for investments in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas in order to revive the economy. The local congress approved a loan of 2,600 million pesos. Until November, no profits from debt were recorded, in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
According to representatives of the business sector, the first year of the government Maria Lópeze Valdése pointed out the lack of governance skills of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, the chairman of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was a lack of the will of the individual sectors, including the government itself of the state.
"The development of the economy in Sinaloa was really small during this year. we have to work intensely to get back the land we lost this year. in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we were missing to harmonize our efforts all and especially the correct and synchronized functioning of this new government. We hope that the next year will be much better," he said.
Slow economy
Loredo López said events like frozen at the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and restricted its development and growth.
"The weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including the colds. One of the main consequences was the slowdown of the economy, which failed to recover quickly enough to re-establish dynamics that would allow to an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services.
Re-definition of mission
According to Teodor Salazar Uriarte, President of the Employer Confederation of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, it is necessary to push the state to more dynamic productive activities.
We believe it is necessary to prepare a long-term plan in which the goals and economic direction of the state will be redefined, because it is important to mobilize all the potential of material and human resources that Sinaloa has,” he said.
The work that is ahead of us
Chairman Coparmex stressed the importance of setting a vision for the future that would better guide the government’s efforts.
