Mexican Institute of Health Insurance Starts Research on the Gen That Causes Obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance is conducting research to discover the genes responsible for the obesity of children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the Institute of IPN
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to detect the genes that cause obesity in children and young people. The research called "Genetics of Obesity in children and adolescents" will allow to obtain results related to overweight.
In a report, the head of the Research Medical Unit in Biochemistry from the Specialized Hospital of the National Health Center of the 21st Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was established.
This team is based on the support of specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
People can come to the participating IMSS sports centers in the Valle de México, where each summit from 8 hours will be conducted tests for teenagers.
He stressed that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (Mexico State) and since October 8 this activity is also carried out at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Centre (Eastern Mexico State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children will be obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to determine the components and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity, and to track on Mexican children and young people risk factors and thus prevent the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on November 14, he reminded that the goal is to collect data from three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years, with the consent and under the supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutritional questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney insufficiency.
He clarified that every Saturday, all participants are performed anthropometric measurements (weight, height, belt circle), blood pressure is measured, the level of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin is determined, and genes are examined (there are attempts to identify the genes that are involved in the formation of childhood obesity).
Cruz López said this research reflects the concerns of healthcare professionals about the alarming increase in child weight.
“Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years only boys had an increase in obesity by 77% and girls by 47%.
He said that one of the reasons for searching for indicators is the assumption that the country’s population is different from the other populations by its genetic history.
He that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in the genes that are responsible for the development of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that generally obesity genetics is commonly explained as the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they get a total assessment of the child’s condition, thus finding out whether they show some known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearms indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-diabetes conditions.
For now, the information is confidential, the doctors transmit it in writing to the parents and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make in order to avoid their children from the disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sitting way of life meaning a lack of daily physical activity, a day-to-day sitting in front of TV and using transportation instead of walking on short distances.
Overweight is also caused by high calorie intake, i.e. greater consumption of sweetened drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no excuses in Asfalt.
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the UNAM Chemical Faculty, creates modified asphalt with polymers and thus creates a mixture with better functionality, regardless of climate conditions and temperature.
If the clay was properly carried out, 200 thousand clay would not need to be repaid after every rain period in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de México, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who also added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt clay were adequate, there would be a significant limitation of clay or even it would be possible to completely remove them.
In his lecture The Technological Cause of Clashes, which he spoke in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalt with polymers, thus creating a mixture with similar characteristics as asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climate, for example in some cities in the north of the country.
He explained that asphalt, the heavest part of oil, is a group of carbohydrate molecules, molecules with a large molecular weight, which are called asphaltens, and others with a low molecular weight, which are called maltens.
The viskoelastique character of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures it has a tendency to break, he added.
This means that the asphalt resistance in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperature, the chemical engineering expert pointed out.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered by a flexible plate that consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers is an asphalt insert, formed by small stones wrapped in asphalt and then pressed.
He emphasized that every stone that forms the insert is filled with asphalt.
When passing the cars or creating pressure, it is possible that the forces in the plate are well distributed.
If it were a modified asphalt, they would dissolve even better, a chemical engineer believes.
He added that on the asphalt insert is placed the last layer called a coat, formed by fine stones, i.e. sand also wrapped in asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with the rafts of the vehicles, it must have greater mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and must ensure the traction of the road.
Since as part of the sliding will be exposed to a large burden, the coat must have a sufficient thickness and must be careful about the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially moisture and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. especially water has a great impact on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the ground is wet, the water spreads inside and it’s hard to get out, it causes the softening of all layers of the plate and thus the formation of moulds.
He explained that during the creation of the scratches the film of the coat is first destroyed and only then the asphalt insert is damaged. The damage does not occur at one moment, but it is a slow process that should be stopped already at the first signs using appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load of the vehicles is another important factor in the formation of clay, and therefore the thickness of each layer of the plate must correspond to the load of the vehicles and must ensure that this load does not exceed.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that when it comes to asphalt, a lot of work is still waiting for us and research is at the beginning. It is worth mentioning, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and allow easy repairs without having to use high temperatures.
