Registration of the Golden Rule on the Balanced Budget in the Constitution
The government of the large coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats, which is in power in Austria, decided on Tuesday to insert the "gold rule" of budgetary policy into the constitution in order to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid the possible reduction of Austria's rating by rating agencies (AAA).
It was the social-democratic chancellor Werner Faymann who announced this decision at the end of the ministerial council in a situation where the Austrian public debt is with its 74.6% high above the maximum criterion of 60% established by the Maastricht Agreement, but much lower than the debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency was reduced by only one degree from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros more on interest each year,” said Michael Spindelegger, a multi-chancellor and Foreign Minister.
Austria follows the summit of the Eurozone countries held in Brussels on October 26, 2011, where the heads of states and governments strongly demanded that the reduction of public deficit and the achievement of balance of public accounts be included in the constitution or in the law of the same value by the end of 2012.
The instrument adopted by the Austrian government is closer to the "German model", Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the public structural deficit will have to fall every year by 0.75% of the GDP (Gross Domestic Product) and starting in 2017, the public structural deficit of the federal state will not be allowed to exceed 0.35% of the GDP every year, while the federal countries, as well as municipalities, will have to report a balanced budget.
The objective is to get the public debt below the criterion of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty in the 2020/21 years.
