Nord Stream, the new port of Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream remote pipeline linking Eastern Europe directly to Russia and led by the bottom of the Baltic Sea began to work.
It must supply a gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to properly celebrate this event.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of states and governments, took part on Tuesday in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte turned together control around the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
This new pipeline will begin to flow 27,5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas to Western Europe each year by the first pipeline of 1,224 km of length connecting the region of St. Petersburg with the federal country of Mecklemburgo-Pomorana.
The second pipeline, which must be completed by the end of 2012, will enable the supply of a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, which is the amount equal to the total French consumption.
And it is already reminded of the possibility of building a third pipeline of the gas pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this enormous building is a victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries protest strongly.
In fact, the Nord Stream will enable the gas to be supplied directly to Germany without being led by any third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are somewhat losing power: the possibility of pressing Russia with threats of closing access to the Western European markets becomes more difficult for them.
Warsaw most strongly expressed this when it did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet Pact", with reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that it is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, with its support to this Russian project, has gained greater certainty in its purchases.
But it is at the expense of weakening Europe’s energy, as the project created breaks between Europeans from the east and the west.
Just five years ago, Russia managed to fulfill its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries with high gas consumption, whose deposits are approaching their end.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that connects us organically,” François Fillon confirmed at the ceremonial opening of this pipeline and demonstrated at what point the big gas contracts are of both political and economic matters.
All this explains the widespread smile of the leaders of Gazprom present in large numbers in Lubmin, a gas supply site.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an important technical act.
The submarine pipeline is made of steel equipped with a concrete coat to be protected from boats of marine vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, it was necessary to avoid the mining fields originating during World War II.
“For security reasons, almost a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed,” says Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal serpent weighing as 242 Eiffel bears, which for its entire length is not interrupted by either valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it when the Swedish were just a little willing to see the Russian state company as it permanently settles on their coast.
“In the event of a defect, we will stop the passing of the gas in less than 1 minute,” says Jens Müller.
In the case of intestine, the gas contained in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered to be unlikely for the builder, since the puzzles were designed so that the impairment arises once every 100,000 years.
The control of the gas pipeline from the outside is carried out by a submarine robot drawn by the ship, while the gas pipeline inside is controlled by the device that circulates inside.
This cigarette-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is introduced to the inside of the pipe and is pressed by gas.
In the destination after all three days of the journey at a speed of 3 m/s, it will provide accurate information about possible deformations of metal parts.
The remote gas pipeline was designed to work for fifty years without any minimum repairs.
Gas circulation is easily secured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the target.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
The leading position remains Gazprom, which holds a share of 51%.
It was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15,5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies created a joint venture called Nord Stream responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
The company has its headquarters in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
The Gazprom subsequently rented the company for a five-year contract, which can be renewed, all its capacity for gas transport.
“Gazprom will have profits from its overall capacity, no matter how much gas it is actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
The funding of the gas pipeline was provided by 30% shareholders and 70% bank loans.
The total cost of work is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both pipes.
For GDF Suez, the investment costs amounted to 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are sure that their costs will be returned, since the risk is taken by Gazprom alone.
The gas pipeline rises from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with borovic forests.
The 4.5 meters high valves form the gas output gate.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the coming gas before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
If the full capacity is achieved, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
